# Constant Fold Trigonometric Functions

## Description

Evaluates trigonometric functions (SIN, COS, TAN, ASIN, ACOS, ATAN,
ATAN2, RADIANS, DEGREES) at compile time when arguments are constants.

**When to apply**: Trigonometric function with all-constant arguments.

**Why it works**: Trigonometric functions are pure and deterministic.
They are more expensive than basic arithmetic, making folding
more beneficial.

## Implementation

```rust
rw!("fold-sin"; "(sin ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", f64::sin) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-cos"; "(cos ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", f64::cos) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-tan"; "(tan ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", f64::tan) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-asin"; "(asin ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", f64::asin) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-acos"; "(acos ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", f64::acos) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-atan"; "(atan ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", f64::atan) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-atan2"; "(atan2 ?a ?b)" => { Fold2("?a", "?b", f64::atan2) } if both_const("?a", "?b")),
rw!("fold-radians"; "(radians ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", to_radians) } if is_const("?a")),
rw!("fold-degrees"; "(degrees ?a)" => { Fold1("?a", to_degrees) } if is_const("?a")),
```

## Test Cases

```sql
-- Before
SELECT SIN(0) FROM t;
-- After
SELECT 0.0 FROM t;
```

```sql
-- Before
SELECT COS(PI()) FROM t;
-- After folding PI then COS:
SELECT -1.0 FROM t;
```

